title: The diameter of the bearing cup housing is too lar; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_4087
description: The diameter of the bearing cup housing is too large. This makes the tolerance between the bearing cup and the hub housing too big, leading to lack of retention of the bearing cup that consequently spins inside the housing. This creates metal and contamination that affects other components such as the bearing rollers or spindle  that got pitted increasing the amount of metal in the wheel hub compartment.

title: Boilermakers aren't following the Schlam procedure; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_4556
description: Boilermakers aren't following the Schlam procedure for welding the saddle supports in the right location. They are just welding them out wherever Schlam has tacked them from the factory. I am sure this is a contributing factor, but given the correlation between shimming and mode light damage, I feel that whilst we should be following the procedure for welding out the saddle properly the shimming is the main factor. If we find trucks with perfect shimming damaging mode lights, then in some of those cases the location of the welded saddle supports should be reviewed as a next step to eliminate this issue.

title: The engine failed due to debris from the engine re; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_4709
description: The engine failed due to debris from the engine rebuild restricting oil flow to bearing 9 and 10 ( they started making their own metal due to lack of oil). This debris may have been filtered out if we had a fully functional engine oil filtration system. As 3 out of 4 bypass valves were installed backwards, they allowed unfiltered oil to flow freely through the bypass passages. This unfiltered oil kept circulating debris and metal particles until the number 10 conrod big end bearing failed.

title: Run a project to improve 994H Final Drive life; Historical BMS Id: RCAACT-0000579
description: Below are the recommendations from this RCA and would be helpful in carrying out further investigation;  1. Align brake cooling oil replacement interval at CB with SM and CC. At CB, brake cooling (36L capacity) is being replaced at 2,000 hr service interval. At CC and SM, same oil is being replaced at 700 hrs interval.  2. Field testing/troubleshooting using an external source to pressurise individual brake packs, can potentially create problems with pressure spikes and over pressurising. WesTrac Tech recommendation is don?t pressurise past 1350-1400 psi when checking ability for brake pack to hold pressure.  3. Change the pressure setting in Cat 994H Service Brake Bypass test SWI (CB-01035-WI-MN-0143) from 1500 psi to 1400 psi when using external source such as Enerpac. Please refer to section 7.8 in the document for the pressure limits. Centralize this document for other sites to use the same SWI.  4. Utilise Westrac's return to work document after each final drive fitment. Please see attached '"994H Brake Bypass Failure Investigation" document for reference. It would be advantageous to make this document as a FMG controlled document and attached to PRT list for SAP final dive c/o work orders.  5. Add an operation item in the final drive c/o work order to clean the brake cooling tank prior to fit the new final drive. This would resolve the contaminant issues arising from brake cooling tank. Cleaning brake cooling tank would take 3 hrs by 1 fitter.  6. Review the repair guidelines around the brake piston seal seating area for quality assurance. Incorrect machining of the seal seating area can cause piston seals to dislodge with time.   7. Investigate the co relation between the heat separation tyre failures on front position and respective final drive failure. It is suspected that tyre heat separation failures may cause excessive stress on the final drive brake pack assy.

title: 03:01: Kartajirri Powerstation Generator GN093 shutdown and SUB009 SWB01 CB01 open – loss of power to Village, Wastewater Plant and Potable Water Plant.
description: 03:03: Phone calls made by Mine Services Electrical Supervisor Dean Williams to gather personnel to investigate. Matthew Fox, Thanesh Patgunarajah (HV Electricians) and Sam Dick (HV Fitter) where called. 03:15: All personnel met at Kartajirri Powerstation for discussion and plan of action. 03:20: Check Powerstation main DEIF controller and noticed unresponsive and alarmed due to low control voltage from batteries. 03:20: Check and acknowledge faults on all Generator DEIF and EMCP Cat controllers. 03:22: Noticed DB10 Q1 Circuit Breaker was tripped. Disabled Ground Fault Protection. Reset ok. 03:25: Check and acknowledge faults on SUB009 DEIF controller. 03:30: Check SUB009 High Voltage Switchgear, SEL relays and transformers for faults. No visible faults to HV equipment and no faults/ events on SEL relays. 03:40: Total loss of voltage to main DEIF HMI screen (blank screen) 03:45: Tested voltage on Powerstation main DEIF controller (7Vdc) meant to be 24Vdc. 03:50: Set up spare batteries found in container to supply voltage to main DEIF controller. 03:50: Check all camp RMU’s for faults or visible damage. No faults or sign of damage. 04:00: Spare batteries not supplying enough voltage. 04:15: Remove 2 batteries from GN091 to supply control voltage to main DEIF controller.  04:30: Connect batteries to main DEIF controller. 04:42: Main DEIF controller powered up and HMI responsive. Acknowledge all alarms. 04:44: Close SUB009 SWB01-CB01 and put SUB009 DEIF controller in Auto. 04:45: Acknowledge faults again on GN092 and GN093. Place both generators into Auto mode. 04:45: Generators GN092 and GN093 start up automatically. 04:46: SUB009 CB03 Closes – Power restored to Village successfully.; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_3506

title: Investigate re-designing of pinion assembly oil level sensor and sight glass with Metso; Historical Sharepoint Eliwana Id 12
description: 22/03/21 DC - Metso's response received 22/3: The oil in the pinion assembly MUST be filled via the filling port in the pinion assembly NOT the by the site glass. The lower hose is situated at the bottom of the pinion assembly so oil will not flow from the site glass to the pinion. When the oil is filled through the filling port, head pressure will force it through the hose and the levels will equalise between the site glass and pinion assembly. As AB has stated before, there are hundreds of these operating in the field with no issues reported if they are set up correctly and commissioned. 17/3/21 DC - Due date extended, still no feedback from Metso 3/3/21 DC - Still awaiting feedback from Metso

title: Engine coolant samples did indicate that TH water ; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_3345
description: Engine coolant samples did indicate that TH water hardness and chloride result indicates poor water quality. This would suggest that the coolant had been getting toped up with water, meaning that something had been consuming the coolant weather it had been from a leak or is had been consumed in the cylinder chamber.   Looking at the engine oil analysis samples for July  prior to the failure they came back with an action comment - The sodium, molybdenum and potassium may indicate a coolant leak. Monitor the amount of coolant use closely. The coolant entry may have been a contributing factor in the build-up of carbon build-up on the intake valve stems and intake and exhaust valve sealing areas as this build up can result from incomplete combustion.  This then may have been contributing factor in the chordal valve and/or valve seat failure.

title: Wheel group was in poor condition Bearings were fa; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_2692
description: Wheel group was in poor condition Bearings were failing, significant spalling evident  Heavy wear and debris damage to bearing journals on spindle Both hub bearing bores measure oversize Debris damage to both planetary gear sets Many broke teeth in the brake friction disks  Given the poor condition of a lot of the wheel end, it can be assumed that this was rebuilt to the higher end of CAT specifications and the parents metal has been through multiple life cycles. Play in the reaction hub could have causes the teeth on the brake friction disks to break, broken teeth would have causes further damage to the disk wear surfaces.  Generated debris from the brake pack would have eventually traveled through to the hoist pump, and eventually caused failure through starvation of oil due to blocked screens. Different brake measurements were likely due to the park brake piston not sitting flat when measurements were taken, this is an inherent problem of this measurement method.

Currently the swing box header tanks are fitted wi; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_3015
description: Currently the swing box header tanks are fitted with caps P/N 7401726. These caps can breath slightly to accommodate the small oil level changes caused by dilatation due to temperature. The air flow that these caps can handle does not allow to leave them in place during the oil change operation as this would create excessive pressure when filling, and prevent from a correct draining. When these caps are removed during the oil draining, this can lead to dust entry into the reservoirs. Further to this, these caps can easily get blocked by wet dust, leading to the reservoir not being able to breath anymore. This requires regular cleaning or replacement of the caps.

Mechanical failure - Main apron support frame atta; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_1629
description: Mechanical failure - Main apron support frame attachment weld failed, due to cracking.  - The cracks initiated at both ends of the apron top flange weld to the chassis.  - The cracks then propagated longitudinally along the beam towards the midspan.  - Initial part of fracture surface was heavily corroded, which indicates that the original damage occurred some time ago. - Due to continues use of the trailer and dynamic loading in this area the crack kept on propagating over time until final failure. - The crack initiation point was located within the heat affected zone of the main chassis structural welds.  - Use of dissimilar materials could have lead to cracking. Apron support frame were made from GR350 carbon steel plate and chassis from cast iron.

Alarm details were as follows: 1. 25/08/2019  11:30:34 AM - Duration 35.4 minutes 2. 25/08/2019  12:09:47 PM - Duration 46.1 minutes 3. 25/08/2019  01:26:12 PM - Duration   5.0 minutes 4. 25/08/2019  01:32:55 PM - Duration 31.3 minutes 5. 25/08/2019  02:29:19 PM - Duration 25.7 minutes According to the OEM the machine should be derated by 25%, when these alarms occur. The condition remained for fairly long periods at a time. No evidence could be found to show that the derating actually occurred. The elevated turbo temperatures would have resulted in reduced strength of the turbo shaft material.

title: Although shock loading may have been the catalyst ; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_1688
description: Although shock loading may have been the catalyst to failure, it is not believed to be the root cause. Upon strip down inspection at Hoffman's Engineering there appeared to be major damage caused by lack of lubrication and build up of dirt within the bearings and grease. Without proper lubrication the axial rollers have become damaged; causing some to rotate 90 deg within the race, break into pieces with fragments of the rollers further embedding into the contaminated grease. With the amount of damaged sustained to the nose ring and rollers, the lack of lubrication had been an issue for an extended amount of time causing extensive damage during this period.

title: CAT Service magazine M0096155-00 introduces new cy; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_1188
description: CAT Service magazine M0096155-00 introduces new cylinder pack components. The new cylinder pack components improve engine reliability and durability. The new cylinder liner has an anti-polishing sleeve and upper liner seal with improved thermal properties. The piston has a rectangular steel compression ring and rectangular steel intermediate ring. The new cylinder pack components are direct replacements for the previous cylinder packs components. However, the replacement with the new cylinder packs must be done for every cylinder in the engine. The new cylinder packs are not compatible to be run with the previous cylinder packs in the same engine.

title: When modified by the supplier, they replaced 1 x c; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_862
description: When modified by the supplier, they replaced 1 x cast shell end on each unit and re-used the other (OEM) shell end.  The original intention was to replace both ends but due to the urgency to deliver they decided to replace one end only (to reduce time frame). When re-using the OEM ends, the supplier modifies them by machining internally and a custom insert is fitted (As a result, from the shell ID, the ligament distance to main water flange bolt holes PCD is slightly reduced). Technically this is slightly weaker than OEM, however according to the supplier if the bolts are torqued correctly they are generally no problem.  Another supplier mitigation is to fit special labels to the shell and on the wrapping, that clearly warn of safe handling and bolt tightening procedures. The supplier noted the OEM shell end which has the correct metric threads also suffered multiple cracked bolt holes, pointing to an anomaly that is not a result of the rebuild (there are at least 10 x cracked bolt holes in different locations).  The supplier’s initial thoughts on the cause were either the Heli-coils did not provide enough thread engagement and/or cast-iron material maybe to be too soft, however both shell ends were affected. There were no Heli-coils in the OEM shell end. Is it recommended the technician installing the coolers use a torque wrench to tighten the bolts as recommended on the labels.  The supplier has used this design for over 15 years and are aware the small M10 bolts on the PCD having a propensity to be over-tightened, the use of our warning labels on safe handling and correct bolt tightening has all but eliminated any issues.

title: The SN215 Screen is supposed to have a 200 PCD Dri; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_566
description: The SN215 Screen is supposed to have a 200 PCD Drive Pulley as opposed to the 190 PCD on the other 2 screens. This was specified by Scheck when the upgraded SLD4385WX Galvanized screen was installed. Orbital plots and a visual inspection was completed on all 3 screens SN214, SN215 & SN216, with the following noted: - 8% difference in speed between screens SN214 / SN216  and SN215. - SN214 -  835 RPM - SN215 – 773 RPM (8% slower) - SN216 – 836 RPM - All orbits appeared similar across the 3, with SN215 showing more variation in movement attributed to overloading at current speed The plug weights on exciters were found to be missing resulting in incorrect orbital. However, its been replaced, and Con Mon is to monitor henceforth. The VEGA Sensor was wired incorrectly, it wasn't tested for functionality before commissioning.

title: Failure is consistent with an over pressured pipe.; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_465
description: Failure is consistent with an over pressured pipe. The section of pipe that was removed is PN12.5, 110mm diameter. The max pressure for this pipe is 1250kpa, at 20*, life span of 50yrs. There is a diaphragm relief system on the discharge line from the pressure side of the pump. This does not seem to be working, however after pipe pressure limits were confirmed at 1250kpa and the line was re energized the system pressure was sitting at 900kpa. There is no feedback to the plant operating system to be able to trend any pressure spikes in the system.

title: 793F engine oil flushing procedure; Historical BMS Id: RCAACT-0000052
description: OEM has confirmed of not having specific engine flushing procedure after engine component's failure. However Westrac PSA has suggested a flushing method for the engine lubrication system. This needs to be communicated to all truck supervisors/coordinators. This method stated that;  "As a minimum you would need to inspect and clean the oil pump and pressure regulator, engine oil coolers, sump and filter housing. If the fuel pump was the cause of failure you will also have to inspect the front gear train, if the fuel pump wasn?t the cause of failure then it would be advisable to drain the oil from the fuel pump sump and inspect the bottom end of the pump as much as possible without disassembly. On top of this I would advise you to clean all external oil lines and inspect where the oil enters the block to see if there is any trace of metal there.  Once the inspection is carried out it would be best to get the machine back to the workshop and drain the engine oil, inspect and change the filters and inspect the sump after 10hrs of operation, if that is all clear then do the same again after 50hrs, if that is all clear then depending on how far away the next planned service is depends on whether you would need to do the same again."

Two final drive types exist on CAT diggers - Bonfi; Historical BMS Id: AT-9999999_2551
description: Two final drive types exist on CAT diggers - Bonfiglioli F series and Rexroth GFT series. The majority of final drives at Cloudbreak are Bonfiglioli F series - Which are drained at both the high and low speed housing sides, But filled only from the low speed side as the two chambers are connected by a common passage. A few machines have GFT drives fitted - Which are similarly drained at both the high and the low speed housing sides, however MUST be filled from both the high and low speed sides as the chambers are seperated by a seal.  For the Bonfiglioli F series: The fluid level is checked by a level plug on the low speed housing.  A Sight glass also exists on the high speed housing, but may be overlooked as the two compartments are common.  For the Rexroth GFT series: The low speed fluid level is checked by a level plug on the low speed housing. The high speed fluid level is checked by a sight glass on the high speed housing.
